Green was born in 1946 as the son of a Jewish working-class family in the Bethnal Green district of London.
At a young age, he was enthusiastic about American blues musicians such as B.B. King and Muddy Waters.
At the age of eleven, he learned the first guitar grips.
At the age of 15, the teenager started playing professional guitar and five years later got the chance to be a lead guitarist for the instrumental band Peter B's Looners on stage.
A little later, he was hired as a replacement for his idol Eric Clapton at the Bluesbreakers.
In the middle of the Blues boom, Green founded Fleetwood Mac in the summer of 1967 along with his Bluesbreakers colleagues Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
The song "Albatross" composed by Green gave the group the first number one hit in the winter of 1968/69 and catapulted them to the top of the British music scene.
But the rapid ascent soon showed its dark sides: Green did not cope with the media buzz, his experiments with the drug LSD became increasingly extreme.
He later commented on the life between music and addiction in an interview: "The worst thing that happened to me in life is the drugs - the best thing was to land a number 1 hit."
Towards the end of the decade, Green succeeded surprisingly in 1979 with an album inspired by religious themes.
Fleetwood Mac, meanwhile, swims on a wave of success without him in a new formation.
Their 1977 album "Rumours" sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite several minor solo successes, Green did not make a major comeback until he re-launched his career with a group of friendly musicians in 1996.
The British Daily Telegraph spoke of a rock star returning to Earth.
Free of drugs, Green released several albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group until the band disbanded in 2004.
For music experts, he was a blues legend during his lifetime - and with his gentle sound one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
